div.p:
I prevailed on this lovely maid to attend the methodiſt preaching at five o'clock on Monday mornings, and we often met at three or four; ſo that we had an hour or two to ſpend in walking and converſation on ſpiritual affairs. Had you ſeen and heard us on the cold froſty mornings, it would have put you in mind of Milton's Devils, whom he repreſents as at times ſtarving with cold:
"Others apart, ſat on a hill, retir'd,
"In thoughts more elevate, and reaſon'd high
"Of Providence, foreknowledge, will, and fate;
"Fix'd fate, free-will, foreknowledge abſolute;
"And found no end in wandering mazes loſt." Paradiſe Loſt.

